            "id": "ap1",
            "title": "Intro to path",
            "gdoc": "https://docs.google.com/document/d/1BbKXQBlcnq7FzrQFX_wbtG-DvKbB6ncPgyOjPRmHyiE/edit",
            "nlm": "https://notebooklm.google.com/notebook/51e78f90-e04f-4557-ba74-da75654fc6cd",
            "content": "Tab 1\n An image of school supplies on a surface, including pencils, notebooks, and a calculator. \n\n\n\nIntroduction to pathology\n\n\nOwner\n\t\n\n\tInstructor\n\t\n\n\tSubject\n\tPathology\n\t\n\nListen to this tab\nIntroduction to Pathology\nPathology is the foundational branch of medical science focused on the study and diagnosis of disease. It serves as the bridge between basic science and clinical practice.\n________________\n\n\nThe Major Branches of Pathology\nPathology is broadly divided into two main fields: Clinical Pathology and Anatomical Pathology.\n1. Clinical Pathology\nThis specialty involves the laboratory examination of bodily fluids (like blood and urine), tissues (biopsy samples), surgically removed organs, and in some cases, the entire body (autopsy).\n2. Anatomical Pathology\nAlso referred to as morbid anatomy , this medical specialty focuses on diagnosing diseases by examining organs, tissues, and cells. Practitioners use both macroscopic (visible to the naked eye) and microscopic evaluations of biopsies and autopsy specimens to identify abnormalities and determine the cause of disease.\n________________\n\n\nSub-specialties of Anatomical Pathology\nAnatomical Pathology itself is divided into several key areas:\nA. Surgical Pathology\nThis is the study and diagnosis of diseases by examining tissue biopsies with a microscope. Before a sample can be viewed, it must undergo a preparatory procedure called tissue processing.\nThe 10 Steps of Tissue Processing\nTissue processing is a fixed sequence of steps used to prepare a biopsy sample for microscopic examination.\n1. Fixation: The tissue is preserved (usually in formalin) to prevent decay and maintain its structure.\n2. Grossing: The pathologist macroscopically examines the specimen and selects the key pieces of tissue to be analyzed.\n3. Dehydration: Water is removed from the tissue, typically by using progressively higher concentrations of alcohol.\n4. Clearing: The alcohol is replaced with a solvent (like xylene) that can mix with the infiltration medium (wax).\n5. Infiltration: The tissue is soaked in molten paraffin wax, which seeps into all the spaces previously held by the clearing agent.\n6. Embedding: The wax-infiltrated tissue is placed in a mold and surrounded by more molten wax, which then hardens into a solid \"block.\"\n7. Sectioning: The hardened wax block is cut into extremely thin slices (sections) using a specialized instrument called a microtome.\n8. Dewaxing: The paraffin wax is dissolved and removed from the thin tissue section, usually with xylene.\n9. Staining: Dyes (most commonly Hematoxylin and Eosin, or H&E) are applied to the tissue section. These stains color different cellular components (like the nucleus and cytoplasm) differently, making them visible.\n10. Mounting: A protective coverslip is placed over the stained section on the glass slide, preparing it for microscopic review.\nB. Cytology\nCytology is the study of individual cells or small clusters of cells to make a medical diagnosis. This is different from surgical pathology, which looks at the structure of the entire tissue. (e.g., Pap smears, fine-needle aspirates).\nC. Autopsy Pathology\nThis branch focuses on the examination of deceased individuals to determine the cause, manner, and circumstances of death. It involves a systematic dissection and analysis of the body's organs and tissues to understand the disease processes or injuries that contributed to the death.\nTypes of Autopsy\n1. Coroner's Autopsy (Forensic Autopsy)\n   * This is a legal investigation ordered by a coroner (an official who investigates violent, sudden, or suspicious deaths ) or a medical examiner.\n   * It is conducted for legal purposes in cases such as:\n      * Suspicious, unnatural, or violent deaths.\n      * Deaths related to criminal investigations.\n      * Patients who die within 24 hours of hospital admission.\n      * Patients who are \"Brought In Dead\" (BID) to a hospital.\n2. Family or Hospital Autopsy (Medical/Voluntary Autopsy)\n   * This type of autopsy is not required by law but is performed to gain medical knowledge.\n   * Family Autopsy: This is conducted with the consent of the deceased's family. The goal is to better understand the illness that led to death or to identify potential inherited (genetic) diseases.\n   * Hospital Autopsy: This is requested by the hospital, also with family consent, to better understand the patient's death, often to review the effects of treatment and management.",
            "summary": "Pathology is the foundational branch of medical science focused on the study and diagnosis of disease. It serves as the bridge between basic science and clinical practice."
