            "id": "ha8",
            "title": "Iron Overload",
            "gdoc": "https://docs.google.com/document/d/1gPzfDj8pCyshT_or0-G3jjHUYWGRvHrWE5dyvob88Cg/edit?usp=sharing",
            "nlm": "https://notebooklm.google.com/notebook/972e796a-bd65-4202-9911-2303ee1e262b",
            "content": "Tab 1\n An image of school supplies on a surface, including pencils, notebooks, and a calculator. \n\n\n\nIron Overload\n\n\nOwner\n\t\n\n\tInstructor\n\t\n\n\tSubject\n\tPathology\n\t\n\nI. Introduction & Definition\nIron Overload occurs when there is a chronic excess of iron entering the body compared to what is lost. Because the human body lacks a physiological mechanism to actively excrete excess iron, it builds up over time.\nHaemochromatosis is the specific medical term for the systemic iron overload that eventually causes tissue damage and organ injury.\nII. Genetic Basis of Haemochromatosis\n* Inheritance Pattern: It is an autosomal recessive disorder.\n* Carrier Status: Heterozygotes (carriers with only one copy of the mutated gene) do not typically show clinical symptoms of iron overload, though they may manifest mildly elevated serum iron levels.\n* Gene Location: The mutant gene is located on the short arm of chromosome 6, closely linked to the HLA locus (specifically between HLA-A and HLA-B, but much closer to HLA-A).\n* Expanded Context: This gene is officially known as the HFE gene. Mutations in this gene (most commonly the C282Y mutation) are the primary cause of hereditary haemochromatosis.\n* Demographics: This genetic mutation is highly prevalent in populations of Northern European descent.\nIII. Causes of Iron Overload\nGenetic (Inherited) Causes:\n* Hereditary Haemochromatosis (HFE gene mutation).\n* Thalassaemia major.\n* Hereditary sideroblastic anaemia.\n* Certain hereditary haemolytic anaemias (e.g., Pyruvate kinase deficiency, G6PD deficiency).\n* Congenital dyserythropoietic anaemia.\n* Neonatal haemochromatosis.\n* Congenital atransferrinaemia.\nAcquired Causes:\n* Expanded Context: While the presentation lists this as a category, common acquired causes usually include frequent blood transfusions (often required for chronic anemias), excessive dietary iron intake, or chronic liver diseases (like alcoholic liver disease or hepatitis C) that disrupt normal iron metabolism.\nIV. Aetiology & Pathogenesis\n* The Core Defect: The primary molecular defect occurs in the mucosal epithelium of the gastrointestinal tract.\n* Hyperabsorption: The duodenal mucosa of a patient with haemochromatosis absorbs iron at a much higher-than-normal rate, even when physiological iron concentrations in the body are already sufficient.\n* Expanded Context: This hyperabsorption is driven by a deficiency in hepcidin, a liver hormone that normally acts as the \"brakes\" on iron absorption. Without enough hepcidin, iron continuously flows into the bloodstream.\n* Cellular Accumulation: The excess iron is stored as ferritin and haemosiderin, which heavily accumulate in most cells of the body, particularly in hepatocytes (liver cells) and macrophages.\nV. Pathology (Tissue Changes)\nGross Pathology:\n* Expanded Context: Macroscopically, organs heavily laden with iron—especially the liver and pancreas—become visibly enlarged, firm, and take on a distinct rusty-brown or \"bronze\" coloration.\nHistology (Microscopic Findings):\n* Prominent haemosiderin deposition is visible in many tissues, predominantly the liver and pancreas.\n* In the liver, haemosiderin accumulates first in the peri-portal hepatocytes (near the edges of the liver lobule) and is less concentrated toward the central vein.\n* Iron is mostly seen in the periphery of regenerating liver nodules.\n* Fibrosis begins in the periportal areas, and eventually, fibrous septae grow to traverse the lobules, leading to cirrhosis.\nVI. Clinical Features\nIron accumulation is a slow process occurring over decades. Because of this, actual tissue injury and symptoms typically do not appear until a patient reaches their fifth decade of life (40s).\nGeneral Symptoms:\n* Weakness and lethargy.\n* Unexplained weight loss.\nJoint Manifestations (Arthropathy):\n* Arthralgia (joint pain) commonly involves the 2nd and 3rd metacarpophalangeal joints (knuckles).\n* It can also involve interphalangeal joints and large joints like the knees, which may become swollen and tender.\n* Radiography of hands & wrists shows: Soft tissue swelling, narrowing of joint spaces, irregular articular surfaces, decreased bone density, osteoporosis, and subcortical cysts.\n* Late-stage joint issues include chondrocalcinosis (calcification of cartilage) or calcification of peri-articular ligaments.\n* Synovial fluid from affected joints may contain calcium pyrophosphate and apatite crystals.\nOrgan-Specific Complications:\n* Skin: Noticeable hyperpigmentation (often leading to the historical term \"bronze diabetes\").\n* Nervous System: Peripheral neuropathy may occur, usually secondary to diabetes.\n* Heart: Cardiac arrhythmias and cardiomyopathies are common.\n* Endocrine System: Complications include Diabetes Mellitus, hypothyroidism, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, pituitary insufficiency, testicular atrophy, impotence, and azoospermia.\n* Liver (Hepatic): Hepatomegaly (enlarged liver) and splenomegaly. Patients are at risk for jaundice, oesophageal varices, severe gastrointestinal haemorrhage, hepatocellular carcinoma (liver cancer), abdominal pain, distension, and shock.\nVII. Management and Therapy\nVenesection (Phlebotomy):\n* This is the primary and most effective treatment. It involves the removal of 500mls of blood once or twice weekly.\n* Each session removes about 200mg to 300mg of iron. Over the course of a year, this safely removes 20-25g of stored iron.\n* There is usually an initial decline in blood haemoglobin concentration, but this returns to normal within a few weeks as the body's haemopoiesis (blood cell production) accelerates to replace the drawn blood.\nIron Chelators:\n* Medications like Desferrioxamine (deferoxamine) are explicitly not recommended as first-line therapy for hereditary haemochromatosis. They are less efficient, more expensive, and significantly more inconvenient than standard phlebotomy.\nSupportive Therapy:\n* Targeted treatment of secondary conditions: managing diabetes, controlling cardiac arrhythmias, and treating bleeding oesophageal varices.\n* Hormone replacement therapy for androgens and thyroid hormones if glands have failed.\n* Strict avoidance of alcohol and other hepatotoxins to prevent accelerating liver cirrhosis.",
