            "id": "ph25",
            "title": "NSAIDs",
            "gdoc": "https://docs.google.com/document/d/13eRIqU7wUswO5tGs7KkRc8KHjSfOpxaqQ_rfgFK9ACY/edit?usp=sharing",
            "nlm": "https://notebooklm.google.com/notebook/a3c91023-50c7-4943-861d-04c3b29075e9",
            "content": "Tab 1\n An image of school supplies on a surface, including pencils, notebooks, and a calculator. \n\nNSAIDs\nNSAIDs\n\n\nOwner\n\t\n\n\tInstructor\n\t\n\n\tSubject\n\tPharmacology\n\t1. Overview and Properties\nNSAIDs are widely used to treat rheumatic diseases, inflammation, and pain. While the original agent, Aspirin, showed efficacy, newer NSAIDs were developed to improve the therapeutic profile and mitigate toxicity.\n* Chemical Nature: Most NSAIDs are weak organic acids, with the exception of Nabumetone, which is a ketone prodrug metabolized into an acidic active drug.\n* Chiral Centers:\n   * Racemic mixtures: Ibuprofen, Ketoprofen.\n   * Single enantiomer: Naproxen.\n   * No chiral center: Diclofenac.\n2. Pharmacokinetics\n* Absorption: NSAIDs are generally well-absorbed, and bioavailability is not significantly altered by food.\n* Metabolism: Most undergo phase I (CYP3A or CYP2C group of P450 enzymes in the liver) followed by phase II, or direct glucuronidation (phase II) alone.\n* Distribution: A significant number of NSAIDs are highly protein-bound, with approximately 98% binding to albumin.\n* Enterohepatic Circulation: Many undergo biliary excretion and subsequent re-absorption. Expatiation: This cycle traps the drug in the system longer and is directly correlated with the severity of lower gastrointestinal (GIT) irritation.\n* Synovial Fluid: NSAIDs accumulate in synovial fluid after repeated dosing. Agents with short half-lives often remain in joints longer than their serum half-lives, whereas those with long half-lives disappear from synovial fluid proportional to their serum concentrations.\n3. Pharmacodynamics: Mechanism of Action (MOA)\nThe primary activity of NSAIDs is the inhibition of prostaglandin biosynthesis.\n* Additional Mechanisms:\n   * Inhibition of chemotaxis.\n   * Down-regulation of Interleukin-1 (IL-1) production.\n   * Decreased production of free radicals and superoxide.\n   * Interference with calcium-mediated intracellular events.\n   * Decreased vessel sensitivity to bradykinin and histamine, reversal of inflammatory vasodilation, and effects on T-lymphocyte lymphokine production.\n* Cyclooxygenase (COX) Selectivity:\n   * Aspirin: Irreversibly acetylates and blocks platelets.\n   * Non-selective NSAIDs: These are reversible inhibitors.\n   * COX-2 Selective Inhibitors (Coxibs): These inhibit prostaglandins synthesized by the COX-2 isozyme (induced at the site of inflammation) without significantly affecting COX-1 (found in GIT, kidneys, and platelets).\n4. General Adverse Effects\nNSAIDs share a common adverse effect profile:\n* CNS: Headache, tinnitus, dizziness, and rarely, aseptic meningitis.\n* CVS: Fluid retention, hypertension, edema, myocardial infarction, and rarely, congestive cardiac failure.\n* GIT: Abdominal pain, dyspepsia, nausea, vomiting, and ulcers or bleeding.\n* Hematologic: Rarely thrombocytopenia, neutropenia, or aplastic anemia.\n* Hepatic: Abnormal liver function tests; rarely, liver failure.\n* Pulmonary: Asthma.\n* Renal: Renal insufficiency, renal failure, hyperkalemia, and proteinuria. Expatiation: Nephrotoxicity occurs because these drugs interfere with the autoregulation of renal blood flow, a process typically modulated by prostaglandins.\n5. Specific Drug Classes & Agents\nAspirin (Acetylsalicylic acid)\n* Primary Use: Antiplatelet effects (due to irreversible inhibition of platelet COX enzyme).\n* PK/PD: Serum half-life is 15 minutes; it is not bound to albumin. Alkalinization of urine increases excretion of free salicylate.\n* Contraindication: Patients with hemophilia.\nCOX-2 Selective Inhibitors (Coxibs)\nThese agents do not impact platelet aggregation (mediated by COX-1) but may increase the risk of edema, hypertension, and myocardial infarction.\n* Celecoxib: Benzene sulfonamide derivative. Used for OA, RA, and Juvenile RA. Interaction: Increases plasma concentration of Lithium and Fluconazole.\n* Etodolac: Racemic acetic acid derivative; metabolized via glucuronidation. Increased risk of acute pancreatitis.\n* Meloxicam: Enolcarboxamide; relatively selective for COX-2. Inhibits Thromboxane A2 synthesis at subtherapeutic doses, but not enough to affect in vivo platelet function.\nNon-Selective COX Inhibitors\n* Diclofenac: Phenylacetic acid derivative. Interaction: Voriconazole (a CYP2C9 inhibitor) can increase its toxicity. Available in various forms (topical, ophthalmic, rectal) to reduce GI injury.\n* Diflunisal: Difluorophenyl derivative of salicylic acid. Features a long half-life due to enterohepatic circulation.\n* Flurbiprofen: Propionic acid derivative. Rarely associated with neurological side effects like cogwheel rigidity and tremor.\n* Ibuprofen: Phenyl propionic acid derivative. Interaction: Can antagonize the irreversible platelet inhibition of aspirin, limiting aspirin’s cardioprotective effect.\n* Indomethacin: Indole derivative. Strong anti-inflammatory, can inhibit phospholipase A and C. Used for closure of patent ductus arteriosus and acute gouty arthritis.\n* Ketoprofen: Propionic acid derivative; inhibits both COX and lipoxygenase.\n* Nabumetone: The only non-acid NSAID in current use; acts as a ketone prodrug.\n* Naproxen: Naphthyl-propionic acid derivative; single enantiomer. More favorable cardiovascular risk profile than ibuprofen.\n* Oxaprozin: Propionic acid derivative with a long half-life (50–60 hours).\n* Piroxicam: Enolcarboxamide; long half-life (57 hours) due to extensive enterohepatic circulation.\n* Sulindac: Sulfoxide prodrug; active metabolite is a sulfide. Useful in patients with compromised renal function as it has less effect on renal prostaglandins.\n* Tolmetin: Pyrrole alkanoic acid derivative; rarely used now due to short half-life.\nNon-Acetylated Salicylates\nExamples include Magnesium Choline Salicylate, Sodium Salicylate, and Salicyl Salicylate. They provide anti-inflammatory relief without inhibiting platelet aggregation; preferred for patients with asthma, bleeding tendencies, or renal dysfunction.",
            "summary": "NSAIDs are widely used to treat rheumatic diseases, inflammation, and pain. While the original agent, Aspirin, showed efficacy, newer NSAIDs were developed to improve the therap..."
